<subSubSection lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="357" pageId="29" pageNumber="356" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,1921,2018]" lastBlockId="30.[151,1437,151,1832]" lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="357" pageId="29" pageNumber="356">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1957,1982]" pageId="29" pageNumber="356">Diagnosis</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[322,677,1957,1982]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="356">(Expanded Description below):</emphasis>
Stellate body (R/r= 
<number box="[903,988,1957,1982]" pageId="29" pageNumber="356" value="2.55" valueMax="3.5" valueMin="1.6">1.6–3.5</number>
) with short to elongate arms. Interadial arcs angular. Abactinal and lateral skeleton reticulate with wide meshes covered by skin. Each skin filled region filled with papulae. Short, sharp spinelets present in some species, absent in others. Abactinal/lateral plates each with a large, prominent sharp conical spine with smaller secondary spines present. Marginal plates present from along lateral side from terminal to interradius, but are otherwise similar in morphology to abactinal plates. Skin covers abactinal, lateral and actinal surface, including abactinal, marginal, actinal and furrow spines, one to three (two in most).
</paragraph>
